	<head title="CfPBoK paper entry" />
	<body>
		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2013"></a><br><code>sle2013/paper15</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2013</a> paper:</span><br><i>A Generic Framework for Symbolic Execution</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AndreiArusoaie.html">Andrei Arusoaie</a>, <a href="../profile/DorelLucanu.html">Dorel Lucanu</a>, <a href="../profile/VladRusu.html">Vlad Rusu</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_16">10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_16</a></li>
<li>Original shorter version of <a href="../sle2014s/paper03.html"><em>Symbolic execution based on language transformation</em></a> (SLE 2014 SI)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagM">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> Symbolic execution is a formal-methods technique, and the paper presents a generic, semantics-based symbolic execution framework.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a><ul><li> The framework assumes a formal operational semantics (term rewriting) and systematically extends it to enable symbolic execution.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> It automatically generates a derived (symbolic) language definition from an original semantics, i.e., a generative refinement of semantics artifacts.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
		<footer/>
